103
00:04:40,570 --> 00:04:44,590
So with this quick historical
perspective, looking back

104
00:04:44,590 --> 00:04:48,820
to 1959, looking at the accident
record of jet air transport

105
00:04:48,820 --> 00:04:52,090
aircraft, the numbers have now--

106
00:04:52,090 --> 00:04:53,680
safety is hard to define.

107
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:55,220
We don't measure safety.

108
00:04:55,220 --> 00:04:57,800
We measure the
opposite, accidents.

109
00:04:57,800 --> 00:05:01,060
And the accident rate has
gone down to the point

110
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:05,140
that I think we can
argue the Civil Air

111
00:05:05,140 --> 00:05:06,850
transportation in
the Western world

112
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:09,890
is the safest system ever,
definitely the safest

113
00:05:09,890 --> 00:05:11,160
transportation system.

114
00:05:11,160 --> 00:05:14,570
But right now, I'm ready to
take on nuclear power as well.

115
00:05:14,570 --> 00:05:20,840
But to achieve this, to achieve
the level of safety that

116
00:05:20,840 --> 00:05:24,980
is reflected with such a
profound reduction in accident

117
00:05:24,980 --> 00:05:27,950
rates, requires several
different approaches.

118
00:05:27,950 --> 00:05:33,750
And the historic approach was to
focus on single point failures,

119
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:37,530
make certain that you didn't
have some unwitting accident.

120
00:05:37,530 --> 00:05:41,550
And looking back
through aviation safety,

121
00:05:41,550 --> 00:05:45,140
we have those flashbulb
moments, those accidents

122
00:05:45,140 --> 00:05:49,370
that we in the discipline
remember profoundly

123
00:05:49,370 --> 00:05:52,850
and that the entire
industry used

124
00:05:52,850 --> 00:05:55,940
to drive our new
insights as they

125
00:05:55,940 --> 00:05:59,180
reflected what was going wrong.

126
00:05:59,180 --> 00:06:01,820
For me, perhaps the first
snap bulb industry--

127
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:05,190
and one that's really important
to this more modern age--

128
00:06:05,190 --> 00:06:10,430
was United flight
232 in July of 1989,

129
00:06:10,430 --> 00:06:13,470
where the fan disk
in engine number two,

130
00:06:13,470 --> 00:06:16,460
which was mounted in the tail,
right above where the three

131
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:19,880
hydraulic lines all joined
together, needed to power

132
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:21,690
the control surfaces.

133
00:06:21,690 --> 00:06:23,480
Well, the fan disk blew.

134
00:06:23,480 --> 00:06:27,500
And while there were many things
leading up to the fan disk

135
00:06:27,500 --> 00:06:32,200
blowing apart and blowing
through the hydraulic lines,

136
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:36,200
it in the end highlighted
that at that instant,

137
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:40,340
in flight, given you
had a fan disk that

138
00:06:40,340 --> 00:06:44,690
had design and maintenance
issues that in flight, we

139
00:06:44,690 --> 00:06:46,280
had a single point failure.

140
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:48,740
Now, I particularly
recall this because I

141
00:06:48,740 --> 00:06:53,120
was a freshman in what was then
called the MIT Aeronautical

142
00:06:53,120 --> 00:06:54,300
Systems Lab.

143
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:57,170
We gathered around this
thing called the TV

144
00:06:57,170 --> 00:07:00,080
and watched live
news to watch it.

145
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:04,530
And the McDonnell Douglas
engineer who was briefing CNN

146
00:07:04,530 --> 00:07:07,250
was holding a schematic and
pointing everything out.

147
00:07:07,250 --> 00:07:09,560
And his Brass Rat
was going up and down

148
00:07:09,560 --> 00:07:13,010
in front of the national
news as he described

149
00:07:13,010 --> 00:07:15,020
just how we had
gotten to the point

150
00:07:15,020 --> 00:07:19,800
that one single failure could
make an airplane-- well,

151
00:07:19,800 --> 00:07:23,540
at the time, they said it should
have been considered unflyable.

152
00:07:23,540 --> 00:07:26,870
The second lesson that we
learned that day is that we,

153
00:07:26,870 --> 00:07:32,330
in many cases, safety ends up
being a factor also of people

154
00:07:32,330 --> 00:07:35,360
being able to come together
and work together in new ways,

155
00:07:35,360 --> 00:07:40,640
for Denny Fitch to run back from
his passenger seat and be able

156
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:45,410
to work the throttles while the
crew already in the flight deck

157
00:07:45,410 --> 00:07:48,830
flew around a while, learning
to fly the airplane only with

158
00:07:48,830 --> 00:07:52,940
differential thrust and elevator
trim to the point that they had

159
00:07:52,940 --> 00:07:57,950
something roughly approximating
a landing and something where we

160
00:07:57,950 --> 00:08:02,550
would have expected
everyone to not survive,

161
00:08:02,550 --> 00:08:06,380
to instead have 2/3
of the people survive.

162
00:08:06,380 --> 00:08:10,080
And this accident, we look
back then on both lessons,

163
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:12,320
the single point
failure, but also

164
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:16,260
the role in the crew
on figuring things out.

165
00:08:16,260 --> 00:08:18,680
Now we'll go forward
a little bit more--

166
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:21,630
1995, the Cali accident.

167
00:08:21,630 --> 00:08:27,000
An American Airlines 757
was en route from Miami,

168
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,840
descending down
to land into Cali.

169
00:08:29,840 --> 00:08:30,970
It's a tricky approach.

170
00:08:30,970 --> 00:08:32,820
You can see on the
left the terrain

171
00:08:32,820 --> 00:08:35,730
where you would have to
descend down into the valley

172
00:08:35,730 --> 00:08:39,780
to line up on the final approach
to the land roughly to the south

173
00:08:39,780 --> 00:08:40,710
here.

174
00:08:40,710 --> 00:08:47,370
And unfortunately, the
autoflight system tried to--

175
00:08:47,370 --> 00:08:50,610
apparently thought it
could fly through granite.

176
00:08:50,610 --> 00:08:54,190
There was no terrain information
available to the pilots.

177
00:08:54,190 --> 00:08:57,790
And as I will talk
about a bit more later,

178
00:08:57,790 --> 00:08:59,820
there's also a
question of just what

179
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:02,040
was available to the
pilot for interpreting

180
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:05,760
where their autoflight system
was going to take them.

181
00:09:05,760 --> 00:09:10,170
Now, this accident was in 1995,
and one of the principal things

182
00:09:10,170 --> 00:09:15,150
that was called out was the lack
of terrain situational awareness

183
00:09:15,150 --> 00:09:16,840
for the pilots--

184
00:09:16,840 --> 00:09:20,540
1995 accident.

185
00:09:20,540 --> 00:09:25,040
1993 study by
Koocher and Hansman

186
00:09:25,040 --> 00:09:29,000
looking at terrain
situational awareness,

187
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:32,630
developing those
fundamental insights needed

188
00:09:32,630 --> 00:09:35,120
for Don Boutwell at
Honeywell and others

189
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:38,000
to really develop the enhanced
ground proximity warning

190
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,450
system so that as the industry
recovered from this accident,

191
00:09:42,450 --> 00:09:46,250
they were able to say, but
there is a technical solution

192
00:09:46,250 --> 00:09:48,540
that we can implement.

193
00:09:48,540 --> 00:09:51,050

194
00:09:51,050 --> 00:09:55,220
So it was this
study in building 37

195
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:58,490
in a part task simulator cobbled
together with IRIX machines

196
00:09:58,490 --> 00:10:04,980
that I view as one of those key
moments around the industry,

197
00:10:04,980 --> 00:10:09,890
looking at what is
possible in 1993

198
00:10:09,890 --> 00:10:14,420
and being positioned when we
actually had the accident in '95

199
00:10:14,420 --> 00:10:20,240
to step in and to say
we have solutions.

200
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:26,450
And with this, here's the
data on jet aircraft accidents

201
00:10:26,450 --> 00:10:30,780
for the period
1991 through 2000.

202
00:10:30,780 --> 00:10:33,050
It's divided, each
bar representing

203
00:10:33,050 --> 00:10:35,900
a different category
of the major descriptor

204
00:10:35,900 --> 00:10:37,510
of the type of accident.

205
00:10:37,510 --> 00:10:40,730
In this case, look at the
two big bars that we had

206
00:10:40,730 --> 00:10:42,330
in the 1990s.

207
00:10:42,330 --> 00:10:47,840
The leading types of accidents,
loss of control and next to it

208
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:50,430
CFIT, Controlled
Flight Into Terrain.

209
00:10:50,430 --> 00:10:53,570
And the Cali accident
is a major part

210
00:10:53,570 --> 00:10:56,630
of that big bar
of the fatalities

211
00:10:56,630 --> 00:10:58,730
that we were seeing
because pilots

