00:25:31,700 --> 00:25:34,280
was supporting the entire
development of the National

498
00:25:34,280 --> 00:25:35,000
Airspace System.

499
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:36,500
And I lamented the
fact that the one

500
00:25:36,500 --> 00:25:41,270
course I never took in aviation
at MIT was air traffic control.

501
00:25:41,270 --> 00:25:43,220
So I had to learn all of that.

502
00:25:43,220 --> 00:25:45,380
This is a diagram
of all the systems

503
00:25:45,380 --> 00:25:48,410
that make up the US Air
Traffic Control system.

504
00:25:48,410 --> 00:25:51,350
And it's an imposing system.

505
00:25:51,350 --> 00:25:53,100
So you can see
the numbers there.

506
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:54,740
I'm not going to
go through them.

507
00:25:54,740 --> 00:25:57,660
And it's run by a team of
14,000 air traffic controllers

508
00:25:57,660 --> 00:26:00,160
and a number of other folks
that handle the other functions,

509
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:01,535
the traffic
management functions,

510
00:26:01,535 --> 00:26:03,350
and so on and so forth.

511
00:26:03,350 --> 00:26:08,020
And so anything that
is introduced to this

512
00:26:08,020 --> 00:26:11,230
really needs to be
carefully considered.

513
00:26:11,230 --> 00:26:12,920
Safety is the
number one priority.

514
00:26:12,920 --> 00:26:16,345
And as Amy noted, the current
safety record is excellent.

515
00:26:16,345 --> 00:26:18,220
And so everything that
needs to be introduced

516
00:26:18,220 --> 00:26:21,910
has to be compared to that
record, which I'm sure Brian

517
00:26:21,910 --> 00:26:25,510
will probably get into later.

518
00:26:25,510 --> 00:26:30,130
So over the 31 years since
I graduated, a lot of things

519
00:26:30,130 --> 00:26:31,790
have happened in this system.

520
00:26:31,790 --> 00:26:33,790
There's something called
the Next Generation Air

521
00:26:33,790 --> 00:26:35,540
Transportation
System was deployed.

522
00:26:35,540 --> 00:26:38,137
And this revamped all of the
primary automation systems.

523
00:26:38,137 --> 00:26:39,970
There's a lot of jokes
back in the day about

524
00:26:39,970 --> 00:26:42,830
how the FAA ran systems
on vacuum tubes.

525
00:26:42,830 --> 00:26:44,920
To my knowledge, there
are no more of those.

526
00:26:44,920 --> 00:26:46,340
I'm not entirely sure.

527
00:26:46,340 --> 00:26:48,340
There may be in Alaska
some weather systems that

528
00:26:48,340 --> 00:26:50,480
have vacuum tubes in them,
but for the most part,

529
00:26:50,480 --> 00:26:52,270
the system has been deployed.

530
00:26:52,270 --> 00:26:55,180
And we move a lot more
people and freight today

531
00:26:55,180 --> 00:26:56,750
than we did back
when I graduated.

532
00:26:56,750 --> 00:26:58,550
And the delays are
generally not worse,

533
00:26:58,550 --> 00:27:00,130
which tells you what's working.

534
00:27:00,130 --> 00:27:03,500
So that's the state of the art
over the course of that time.

535
00:27:03,500 --> 00:27:07,480
And where much of my work was is
that the science of air traffic

536
00:27:07,480 --> 00:27:11,680
flow management has
changed radically.

537
00:27:11,680 --> 00:27:14,595
Back in the day, 31 years ago,
the FAA controlled everything.

538
00:27:14,595 --> 00:27:16,720
Now there's a collaborative
decision-making process

539
00:27:16,720 --> 00:27:20,140
where the airlines and the
DOD and other operators

540
00:27:20,140 --> 00:27:22,130
take part in the
management of the system.

541
00:27:22,130 --> 00:27:24,310
And that's been a major advance.

542
00:27:24,310 --> 00:27:26,040
Weather forecasts have improved.

543
00:27:26,040 --> 00:27:28,190
Traffic management
tools have improved.

544
00:27:28,190 --> 00:27:30,667
And so our ability
to do more than just

545
00:27:30,667 --> 00:27:32,250
keep aircraft from
hitting each other,

546
00:27:32,250 --> 00:27:34,333
but rather to make the
whole system more efficient

547
00:27:34,333 --> 00:27:35,130
has improved.

548
00:27:35,130 --> 00:27:36,710
And we've gone to
something called

549
00:27:36,710 --> 00:27:38,280
trajectory-based operations.

550
00:27:38,280 --> 00:27:39,770
And what this means
in practicality

551
00:27:39,770 --> 00:27:43,110
is that when things get
incredibly dense at an airport,

552
00:27:43,110 --> 00:27:46,380
we can manage the flow
by time of arrival.

553
00:27:46,380 --> 00:27:50,600
And because of the deployment
of GPS and other precision

554
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:52,610
navigation systems,
aircraft are much better

555
00:27:52,610 --> 00:27:54,440
at following those
things, provided

556
00:27:54,440 --> 00:27:56,460
that the pilots are
interacting with the system

557
00:27:56,460 --> 00:28:01,780
and not just watching it happen
and it was just talking about.

558
00:28:01,780 --> 00:28:06,400
So just briefly, you guys
probably already know this,

559
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:08,150
but I didn't know it
when I left MIT, so I

560
00:28:08,150 --> 00:28:09,520
figured I would put it in here.

561
00:28:09,520 --> 00:28:10,937
Air traffic control
is what people

562
00:28:10,937 --> 00:28:14,130
know is controllers
separating airplanes.

563
00:28:14,130 --> 00:28:15,420
It's a fairly exact science.

564
00:28:15,420 --> 00:28:16,470
It's well defined.

565
00:28:16,470 --> 00:28:19,530
There are tools that have been
deployed over the past 31 years.

566
00:28:19,530 --> 00:28:23,800
But fundamentally, it's not that
different than it was back then.

567
00:28:23,800 --> 00:28:25,240
A traffic management
where you're

568
00:28:25,240 --> 00:28:29,410
looking out, say, 30
minutes to 24 hours

569
00:28:29,410 --> 00:28:32,410
to plan against things that
are probably going to happen

570
00:28:32,410 --> 00:28:34,540
is something that has been
evolving quite radically

571
00:28:34,540 --> 00:28:36,430
over that time.

572
00:28:36,430 --> 00:28:39,860
And it involves many,
many stakeholders.

573
00:28:39,860 --> 00:28:41,180
It's a bit of an art.

574
00:28:41,180 --> 00:28:44,018
And honestly, there are a lot of
still unsolved problems in this.

575
00:28:44,018 --> 00:28:46,060
And so that's where I'm
going to spend a good bit

576
00:28:46,060 --> 00:28:47,325
of the time in this lecture.

577
00:28:47,325 --> 00:28:50,670

578
00:28:50,670 --> 00:28:53,940
So to get back to weather,
aviation weather forecasting

579
00:28:53,940 --> 00:28:54,610
is challenging.

580
00:28:54,610 --> 00:28:57,550
It's one thing to know if
you're going to hold a picnic,

581
00:28:57,550 --> 00:29:01,300
that it's the 30% chance
of rain this afternoon.

582
00:29:01,300 --> 00:29:03,480
You need much, much
more precise weather

583
00:29:03,480 --> 00:29:04,978
to do anything with aviation.

584
00:29:04,978 --> 00:29:07,020
You need to know whether
a particular routes will

585
00:29:07,020 --> 00:29:09,330
be closed, whether
airports will be closed

586
00:29:09,330 --> 00:29:11,830
or will be impacted
by low visibility.

587
00:29:11,830 --> 00:29:13,620
This is an example
of the absolute state

588
00:29:13,620 --> 00:29:18,070
of the art in long range
thunderstorm forecasting.

589
00:29:18,070 --> 00:29:21,120
Each of those areas, which
are hundreds of miles long,

590
00:29:21,120 --> 00:29:24,120
tell you that there's
maybe a certain likelihood

591
00:29:24,120 --> 00:29:26,790
of thunderstorms happening and
what the likely tops of those

592
00:29:26,790 --> 00:29:28,380
would be.

593
00:29:28,380 --> 00:29:31,480
Planning to this is not
trivial, nor is it precise.

594
00:29:31,480 --> 00:29:35,660
And so the essence of the
modern system is flexibility.

595
00:29:35,660 --> 00:29:37,853
You have a lot of
tools to manage flows.

596
00:29:37,853 --> 00:29:39,270
And so the challenge
is how do you

597
00:29:39,270 --> 00:29:41,370
react to something like this?

598
00:29:41,370 --> 00:29:43,875
Under 90 minutes, we can
watch thunderstorms move,

599
00:29:43,875 --> 00:29:45,250
and we have a
pretty good chance.

600
00:29:45,250 --> 00:29:47,550
So I'm going to talk about are
some of the tools that I've

601
00:29:47,550 --> 00:29:50,008
been involved with developing
and applied my lessons that I

602
00:29:50,008 --> 00:29:54,120
learned here at MIT to
help develop and deploy

603
00:29:54,120 --> 00:29:57,130
and some things that
we haven't solved yet.

604
00:29:57,130 --> 00:29:58,900
So one of the first
things I got involved

605
00:29:58,900 --> 00:30:02,100
with when I left here
was in trying to support

606
00:30:02,100 --> 00:30:03,850
this collaborative
decision-making process

607
00:30:03,850 --> 00:30:06,520
by giving traffic managers
what you would think

608
00:30:06,520 --> 00:30:07,730
would be a very simple thing.

609
00:30:07,730 --> 00:30:08,710
There's weather.

610
00:30:08,710 --> 00:30:10,918
We have a pretty good idea
of where it's going to be.

611
00:30:10,918 --> 00:30:13,293
How do we know which airplanes
are going to encounter it,

612
00:30:13,293 --> 00:30:14,480
and what do we do about it?

613
00:30:14,480 --> 00:30:16,310
So again, simple problem.

614
00:30:16,310 --> 00:30:17,463
They had no way to do this.

615
00:30:17,463 --> 00:30:19,130
You were doing this
incredibly manually.

616
00:30:19,130 --> 00:30:20,290
And so all of this--

617
00:30:20,290 --> 00:30:23,290
all of this did.

618
00:30:23,290 --> 00:30:25,900
We actually pulled a trailer
out at one of the centers

619
00:30:25,900 --> 00:30:27,500
and put a bunch of
computers in it.

620
00:30:27,500 --> 00:30:29,750
And we let traffic managers
come out and play with it,

621
00:30:29,750 --> 00:30:32,650
looking at the real data and
do some tests to get back

622
00:30:32,650 --> 00:30:36,040
to human-centered design
and come up with a system

623
00:30:36,040 --> 00:30:37,748
where you could draw
a polygon or a line,

624
00:30:37,748 --> 00:30:39,540
and you could add a
bunch of filters to it.

625
00:30:39,540 --> 00:30:40,313
And it could move.

626
00:30:40,313 --> 00:30:41,980
And what it would
fundamentally give you

627
00:30:41,980 --> 00:30:43,060
in the middle of
the screen, there

628
00:30:43,060 --> 00:30:44,770
is a list of which
flights were involved

629
00:30:44,770 --> 00:30:49,100
and how many were encountering
it as a function of time.

630
00:30:49,100 --> 00:30:51,620
And what we found was if you
give them something like this

631
00:30:51,620 --> 00:30:54,700
and it was deployed in what was
then called the enhanced traffic

632
00:30:54,700 --> 00:30:57,750
management system, they would
find a million ways to use it.

633
00:30:57,750 --> 00:31:02,330
And so this tool actually is
the basis of a lot of the things

634
00:31:02,330 --> 00:31:05,030
that caused your pilot to
say while you're sitting

635
00:31:05,030 --> 00:31:06,960
on the runway in and
perfectly clear weather,

636
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:10,180
we can't leave because
of air traffic control.

637
00:31:10,180 --> 00:31:13,410
That's actually a good
thing, believe it or not.

638
00:31:13,410 --> 00:31:16,070
But there are things called
airspace flow programs that

639
00:31:16,070 --> 00:31:19,460
keep us from overloading sector
controllers near these weather

640
00:31:19,460 --> 00:31:23,510
areas and a whole host of other
what we call traffic management

641
00:31:23,510 --> 00:31:27,902
initiatives that are planned
by the use of these things.

642
00:31:27,902 --> 00:31:29,610
And one of the things
I learned from this

643
00:31:29,610 --> 00:31:32,018
was that if you give
people a flexible tool,

644
00:31:32,018 --> 00:31:33,810
they will find all
kinds of innovative ways

645
00:31:33,810 --> 00:31:36,180
to use it that you probably
didn't even [INAUDIBLE].

646
00:31:36,180 --> 00:31:39,210
But the most important thing
about giving any kind of tool

647
00:31:39,210 --> 00:31:41,820
to people who have essentially
a full slate of work

648
00:31:41,820 --> 00:31:45,587
on their plate, that the first
thing it has to do is save time.

649
00:31:45,587 --> 00:31:47,170
And that's what
computers are good at.

650
00:31:47,170 --> 00:31:50,860
Have the computer do the
things that are drudgery,

651
00:31:50,860 --> 00:31:52,890
the things that are
difficult, and then

652
00:31:52,890 --> 00:31:55,120
but have it be an interactive
part of the process.

653
00:31:55,120 --> 00:31:57,920
And this was a great
example of that.

654
00:31:57,920 --> 00:32:01,050
The next thing we tried
to do was say, OK,

655
00:32:01,050 --> 00:32:02,710
let's say you take some action.

656
00:32:02,710 --> 00:32:05,420
To move aircraft
around that weather.

657
00:32:05,420 --> 00:32:07,310
What's the impact
of that going to be?

658
00:32:07,310 --> 00:32:09,320
This proved to be
a much harder thing

659
00:32:09,320 --> 00:32:12,145
to get designed appropriately
and for them to do so.

660
00:32:12,145 --> 00:32:13,520
On the left there,
you see a case

661
00:32:13,520 --> 00:32:15,290
where something called
a national playbook

662
00:32:15,290 --> 00:32:16,830
play is being evaluated.

663
00:32:16,830 --> 00:32:18,740
That's a predefined
set of routes

664
00:32:18,740 --> 00:32:21,470
that get around weather
in certain places.

665
00:32:21,470 --> 00:32:24,470
And there is a whole virtual
online book of those.

666
00:32:24,470 --> 00:32:25,970
You can actually
look it up yourself

667
00:32:25,970 --> 00:32:30,640
if you go to the NOAA
status page on the web.

668
00:32:30,640 --> 00:32:33,790
But in this case, it's
going to move possibly

669
00:32:33,790 --> 00:32:34,790
hundreds of airplanes.

670
00:32:34,790 --> 00:32:36,998
And the question is, what
will that do to the system?

671
00:32:36,998 --> 00:32:40,060
And so on the right
is a system that

672
00:32:40,060 --> 00:32:42,218
was deployed that
allows you to test that,

673
00:32:42,218 --> 00:32:44,260
and it tells you how many
airplanes you're moving

674
00:32:44,260 --> 00:32:45,360
from one place to another.

675
00:32:45,360 --> 00:32:47,500
Without getting
into detail, this

676
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:49,060
is a tool for
determining whether you

677
00:32:49,060 --> 00:32:53,430
have the right staffing
in place to handle this.

678
00:32:53,430 --> 00:32:56,970
From the time that this
was developed to the time

679
00:32:56,970 --> 00:33:00,960
that it was deployed
was 17 years,

680
00:33:00,960 --> 00:33:03,880
which is on the long side.

681
00:33:03,880 --> 00:33:06,910
Typical I think the average
time to deploy a new feature

682
00:33:06,910 --> 00:33:08,580
to the NAS is about 10.

683
00:33:08,580 --> 00:33:10,080
But this is what
happens when you're

684
00:33:10,080 --> 00:33:12,247
working with a system that
has to work all the time.

685
00:33:12,247 --> 00:33:15,510
And it's an argument I get into
with my military colleagues

686
00:33:15,510 --> 00:33:18,060
all the time on the
other side of miter where

687
00:33:18,060 --> 00:33:20,110
they can deploy something
in two or three years.

688
00:33:20,110 --> 00:33:24,580
And the difference is ours
have to work all the time.

689
00:33:24,580 --> 00:33:27,220
A military system can
work 95% of the time

690
00:33:27,220 --> 00:33:29,840
and still be acceptable and
still give you an advantage.

691
00:33:29,840 --> 00:33:31,757
And that's a huge
difference when you're

692
00:33:31,757 --> 00:33:32,840
working in an air traffic.

693
00:33:32,840 --> 00:33:36,060

694
00:33:36,060 --> 00:33:38,640
The next step beyond this was
to start thinking about systems

695
00:33:38,640 --> 00:33:40,920
that suggest solutions.

696
00:33:40,920 --> 00:33:43,350
And this is an example
of one that we worked on,

697
00:33:43,350 --> 00:33:46,800
and it employed some
NASA ideas as well.

698
00:33:46,800 --> 00:33:48,780
But basically, the
idea would be instead

699
00:33:48,780 --> 00:33:50,250
of having to
develop those routes

700
00:33:50,250 --> 00:33:53,130
and do what-if examples to test
them and so forth, you could

701
00:33:53,130 --> 00:33:55,620
actually identify for each
aircraft involved, what would be

702
00:33:55,620 --> 00:33:59,080
a reasonably optimal route to
get around a weather situation,

703
00:33:59,080 --> 00:34:00,750
coordinate it.

704
00:34:00,750 --> 00:34:03,270
And then one of the big
problems with rerouting

705
00:34:03,270 --> 00:34:06,370
is you have to collaborate
amongst facilities.

706
00:34:06,370 --> 00:34:09,310
And so this would automate
that coordination.

707
00:34:09,310 --> 00:34:12,610
Again, we did a bunch of
human in the loop testing

708
00:34:12,610 --> 00:34:15,556
and worked through it until
they were satisfied with it

709
00:34:15,556 --> 00:34:16,639
and thought it would work.

710
00:34:16,639 --> 00:34:18,130
It was put into the
deployment pipeline,

711
00:34:18,130 --> 00:34:19,489
and then the funding dried up.

712
00:34:19,489 --> 00:34:23,420
But it is a possible
thing to do.

713
00:34:23,420 --> 00:34:25,070
It's still potentially
on the list,

714
00:34:25,070 --> 00:34:27,800
so maybe someday we'll
see something like this.

715
00:34:27,800 --> 00:34:30,710
But to date, we don't move
aircraft one at a time.

716
00:34:30,710 --> 00:34:32,679
We move them in giant groups.

717
00:34:32,679 --> 00:34:36,120
So that's still the
state of the art.

718
00:34:36,120 --> 00:34:39,070
And the last system I
wanted to talk about

719
00:34:39,070 --> 00:34:40,600
was the problem
of strategic TFM.

720
00:34:40,600 --> 00:34:42,350
The stuff that I was
talking about before,

721
00:34:42,350 --> 00:34:43,517
you saw pictures of weather.

722
00:34:43,517 --> 00:34:46,864
That means we had either
weather radar returns on there

723
00:34:46,864 --> 00:34:49,239
or we had short-term predictions
where you could actually

724
00:34:49,239 --> 00:34:50,949
draw essentially
where you thought

725
00:34:50,949 --> 00:34:52,239
the weather was going to move.

726
00:34:52,239 --> 00:34:54,833
But strategic TFM uses
that initial weather

727
00:34:54,833 --> 00:34:56,500
picture that I saw,
which is that I have

728
00:34:56,500 --> 00:34:58,250
a vague idea of where
the problem is going

729
00:34:58,250 --> 00:35:01,492
to be 12 hours from now, six
hours from now, whatever it is.

730
00:35:01,492 --> 00:35:02,950
And I have a bunch
of aircraft that

731
00:35:02,950 --> 00:35:05,630
are going to take off and maybe
spend five hours in the air.

732
00:35:05,630 --> 00:35:08,460
What do I want to do?

733
00:35:08,460 --> 00:35:12,380
And there's a couple of
problems with this situation.

734
00:35:12,380 --> 00:35:15,980
Number one, typically, when
humans are solving a problem,

735
00:35:15,980 --> 00:35:17,590
they rely on past experience.

736
00:35:17,590 --> 00:35:20,950
You never get the same weather
day twice in the past, really.

737
00:35:20,950 --> 00:35:24,330
And so it's very hard to learn.

738
00:35:24,330 --> 00:35:26,730
The other is you have a bunch
of stakeholders involved

739
00:35:26,730 --> 00:35:29,070
that have different objectives.

740
00:35:29,070 --> 00:35:32,220
The FAA folks want to
protect their controllers

741
00:35:32,220 --> 00:35:34,720
so that they continue to
safely handle the aircraft.

742
00:35:34,720 --> 00:35:37,650
Airlines obviously want
to meet their schedule.

743
00:35:37,650 --> 00:35:42,640
DOD wants to execute their
